results.definition: a deep hole or shaft dug or drilled to obtain water or oil or gas or brine
a cavity or vessel used to contain liquid
an abundant source
examples: she was a well of information

results.definition: an open shaft through the floors of a building (as for a stairway)
an enclosed compartment in a ship or plane for holding something as e.g. fish or a plane's landing gear or for protecting something as e.g. a ship's pumps
come up, as of a liquid
in good health especially after having suffered illness or injury; at least I feel well"
resulting favorably
examples: it's a good thing that I wasn't there
it is good that you stayed
it is well that no one saw you

results.definition: wise or advantageous and hence advisable
examples: it would be well to start early

results.definition: (often used as a combining form) in a good or proper or satisfactory manner or to a high standard (`good' is a nonstandard dialectal variant for `well')
examples: the baby can walk pretty good

results.definition: thoroughly or completely; fully; often used as a combining form
examples: in order to avoid food poisoning be sure the meat is well cooked

results.definition: indicating high probability; in all likelihood
examples: a mistake that could easily have ended in disaster
you may well need your umbrella
he could equally well be trying to deceive us

results.definition: (used for emphasis or as an intensifier) entirely or fully
examples: was well aware of the difficulties ahead
suspected only too well what might be going on

results.definition: to a suitable or appropriate extent or degree
examples: the fetus has well developed organs
his father was well pleased with his grades

results.definition: favorably; with approval
examples: their neighbors spoke well of them
he thought well of the book

results.definition: to a great extent or degree
examples: I'm afraid the film was well over budget
painting the room white made it seem considerably (or substantially) larger
the house has fallen considerably in value

results.definition: with great or especially intimate knowledge
with prudence or propriety
examples: You would do well to say nothing more

results.definition: with skill or in a pleasing manner
in a manner affording benefit or advantage
examples: The children were settled advantageously in Seattle

results.definition: in financial comfort
examples: she has been able to live comfortably since her husband died

results.definition: without unusual distress or resentment; with good humor
